<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Burl_Ives&action=edit&section=15.php.html" title="Edit section: Radio work (selected)[31]">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Radio_work_.28selected.29.5B31.5D">Radio work (selected)<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><i>Back Where I Came From</i>, CBS (30 September 1940 – February 28, 1941)</li>
<li><i>The Wayfarin' Stranger</i>, CBS &amp; WOR (1941–1942, 1946–1948)<sup id="cite_ref-James_R_2003.2C_p._403_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-James_R_2003.2C_p._403-32"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><i>Burl Ives Coffee Club</i>, CBS (5 July 1941 – January 24, 1942)</li>
<li><i>The Columbia Workshop</i>, CBS
<ul>
<li>"Roadside" (March 2, 1941)</li>
<li>"The Log of the R-77," second installment of <i>Twenty-Six by Corwin</i> (May 11, 1941)</li>
<li>"The People, Yes," third installment of <i>Twenty-Six by Corwin</i> (May 18, 1941)</li>
<li>"A Child's History of Hot Music" (March 15, 1942)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><i>G. I. Jive</i>, military radio (c. 1943)<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><i>Columbia Presents Corwin</i>, CBS
<ul>
<li>"The Lonesome Train" (March 21, 1944)</li>
<li>"El Capitan and the Corporal" (July 25, 1944)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><i>The Theatre Guild on the Air</i>, ABC
<ul>
<li>"Sing Out, Sweet Land" (October 21, 1945)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><i>Hollywood Star Time</i>, CBS
<ul>
<li>"The Return of Frank James" (March 10, 1946)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><i>The Burl Ives Show</i>, Syndication (1946–1948)</li>
<li><i>Hollywood Fights Back</i>, ABC (November 2, 1947)</li>
<li><i>The Kaiser Traveler</i>, ABC (24 July – September 4, 1949)</li>
<li><i>Burl Ives Sings</i>, Syndication (1950s)</li>
</ul>
